<h2 id="Data-Exploration">Data Exploration<a class="anchor-link" href="#Data-Exploration">&#182;</a></h2><p>Lets go ahead and visualize the data to try and identify any obvious trends or patterns that we cant see by just looking at the raw data. Starting with a simple bar graph.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[&nbsp;]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1">#Functions for loss vs win averaging </span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">extractParamTeamBased</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">paramName</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">blueWinsSample</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;blueWins&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">blueLossesSample</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;blueWins&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>

    <span class="n">xWin</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">average</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">blueWinsSample</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">paramName</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">xLose</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">average</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">blueLossesSample</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">paramName</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">add_axes</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">])</span>
    <span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;Blue Win&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">&#39;Blue Loss&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="n">xWin</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">xLose</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bar</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;Average of &quot;</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">paramName</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;diff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s2">&quot; between losses and wins&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">paramName</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;diff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s2">&quot; Advantage&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
    
<span class="n">extractParamTeamBased</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diffData</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffKills&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">extractParamTeamBased</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diffData</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTowersDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<p>We can see from the above that in general, the winning team on average has an advantage in most stats compared to different teams. However, this can be misleading as sometimes they can be a function of winning. Such an example is TowersDestroyed. In order to win, you must destroy the enemy's Nexus meaning that the winning team will always have more towers/structures destroyed. We want to focus in on more prefictive parameters as well as other more correlative variables. Lets look at some other ways to visualize our data.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[&nbsp;]:</div>
<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
     <div class="CodeMirror cm-s-jupyter">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">heatMap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">corr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">corr</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">))</span> 

    <span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">corr</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">annot</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;coolwarm&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">.5</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">heatMap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">originalData</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">heatMap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diffData</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<p>From this heatmap we can see that certain variables/parameters are more correlated to blueWin than others. For example both experience and the gold difference between the two teams has a signifiant coreelation to win. Note that Gold per min and average level are byproducts of total gold and total experience. There are other variables that are highly correlated, which we will also ignore, such as blueDeaths and redKills, as each blueDeath is a result of a red kill.</p>
<p>Something else that I am curious about is the win rate between blue side vs red side. When a player enters the game, they are randomly placed on the blue or red team, so in theory they should be just about 50%. However, the map is not identical for both sides, with each side having small differences in obstacles and the map layout. I want to explore whether these differences account for a signficance in the win rate of being on blue or red team.</p>

</div>
</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell   ">
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper">
<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In&nbsp;[&nbsp;]:</div>

</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>From the plot it appears that diffTotalGold and diffTotalExperience have a strong positive correlation when a team wins and almost no correlation when a team loses. What is interesting is that a large positive difference for both variables almost always equates to a win, but a large negative difference for both variables doesn't necessarily equate to a loss. Additionally, there is a large area in the plot roughly centered around (0,0) where both wins and losses are very common. Intuitively this makes sense because evenly matched games mean that the differences in variables for the two teams will be very small, yet one team must lose and another must win.</p>

<p>By looping through the table, it was very simple to collect the win frequency of teams based on groupings of diffGold and diffExperience. By turning this data into bar graphs, it was clear yet again that diffTotalGold and diffTotalExperience are strong predictors for game performance.</p>

<h2 id="Predictor:">Predictor:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Predictor:">&#182;</a></h2><p>Idea here is to train a model to predict outcome of games. In this case, we can choose several different types of models such as Neural Net, Decision Tree, Logistic Regression, and many more. I ultimately decided for kNN binary classifier because of its simplicity, and the fact that we have 40 parameters. Another options that I considered was Neural Nets, however, it requires a lot of fine funing such as types and number of layers, number of nodes per layer, and activation times. I believe that ultimately NN's will be more accurate, but will take a lot more time in terms of training and fitting the model to our dataset.</p>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.neighbors</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">KNeighborsClassifier</span>

<span class="n">originalArr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueWardsPlaced&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redWardsPlaced&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueWardsDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redWardsDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueFirstBlood&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redFirstBlood&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueKills&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redKills&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueDeaths&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redDeaths&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueAssists&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redAssists&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueEliteMonsters&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redEliteMonsters&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueDragons&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redDragons&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueHeralds&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redHeralds&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueTowersDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="s2">&quot;redTowersDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueTotalGold&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redTotalGold&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueTotalExperience&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redTotalExperience&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueAvgLevel&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redAvgLevel&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueTotalMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redTotalMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueTotalJungleMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redTotalJungleMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueGoldDiff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueExperienceDiff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueCSPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="s2">&quot;redCSPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;blueGoldPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s2">&quot;redGoldPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">diffArr</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">&quot;diffdWardsPlaced&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffWardsDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffFirstBlood&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffKills&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffDeaths&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffAssists&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffEliteMonsters&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffDragons&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffHeralds&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTowersDestroyed&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTotalGold&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTotalExperience&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffAvgLevel&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTotalMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffTotalJungleMinionsKilled&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffGoldDiff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffExperienceDiff&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffCSPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;diffGoldPerMin&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1">#Select the columns we want to take into account within our model, since we have two different datasets, we are selecting different columns</span>

<span class="n">X_og</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_og</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">originalData</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="n">originalArr</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">originalData</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;blueWins&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">x_og_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x_og_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_og_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_og_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X_og</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_og</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">42</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1">#Split the data using sklearn&#39;s built in function, which we imported above</span>


<span class="n">neigh_og</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_og_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_og_train</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1">#Train the model, using the dataset</span>


<span class="n">y_pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">neigh_og</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_og_test</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1">#Use the trained model to predict different games which the model hasn&#39;t seen before and check the outcome against what we have, print out the scores for the model</span>

<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">accuracy_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_og_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_pred</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">classification_report</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_og_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_pred</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">confusion_matrix</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_og_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_pred</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1">#####################################</span>
<span class="c1">#Repeat for diff dataset. Same step as above except we use different parameters which we defined above</span>

<span class="n">neigh_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">KNeighborsClassifier</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_neighbors</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">x_diff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">diffData</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="n">diffArr</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">diffData</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="s2">&quot;blueWins&quot;</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">x_diff_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x_diff_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_diff_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_diff_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_diff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_diff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">42</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="n">neigh_diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_diff_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_diff_train</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">y_pred</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">neigh_diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_diff_test</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">accuracy_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_diff_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_pred</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">classification_report</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_diff_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_pred</span><span class="p">))</span>

<h4 id="Model-analysis">Model analysis<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-analysis">&#182;</a></h4><p>From the outcome, we can see that our model works fairly well, although there is certainly room for improvement. After using different types of models such as Decision Tree and NN, the accuracy of all were at or below that of kNN's. I suspect this is due to the fact that we are missing some other explanatory variables such as item or efficiency of gold use by players. This is something that we can build upon with this dataset, since it does not include items that the players bought.</p>
<h4 id="Diff-vs-Original-Data">Diff vs Original Data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Diff-vs-Original-Data">&#182;</a></h4><p>Through running multiple runs of the model, the diff(relative dataset) consistently outperforms the original dataset. This is probably the case because in league it doesn't matter how well you perform, you just have to outperform the other team. The models for diff usually has a 1-2% accuracy edge.</p>

<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h2 id="Final-Thoughts">Final Thoughts<a class="anchor-link" href="#Final-Thoughts">&#182;</a></h2><p>Looking at the data weve pulled we were able to learn a few things: First, the best predictors of win rate are gold, kill, and experience differential. This makes sense as earning a kill in league of legends rewards players with both gold and experience points. Next, we also learned that although these factors have high correlation when trying to predict if a team will win or not, the opposite is not necessarily true for predicting when a team will lose. From a user experience perspective, creators should try to balance the game such that there are clear win conditions and options to improve your chances of winning, but also multiple avenues to make a comeback should things go south. If the outcome of the game was too dependent on gaining leads in gold and experience, then it wouldnt be an enjoyable experience for the losing team. On the other hand, league of legends is considered to be a competitive video game, and having too little of a correlation between those values and winning would also reduce the quality of user experience, as skill expression would be rewarded less and there would be less of an incentive to play the game more and improve. An ideal game would be one that provides a wide window of options for comebacks early on in the game, that gradually reduces as the game goes on.</p>

</div>
</div>
<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<p>Based on these factors stated above, we recommend Riot Games to implement more item diversity with items that have power-spikes at different points in the game. By adding items that are stronger earlier on in the game, players have the option to sacrifice more power later on in order to try to make a comeback in the early to mid game. This would keep the losing team interested even when behind, but also still uphold the advantage that the winning team has and giving both teams a clear win condition: the winning team should try to maintain their item advantage and wait until the losing teams items fall off in power, and the losing team must take advantage of the small window they are given where they are greater than or equal to the winning team in power.</p>
